## Hunt Walkthrough

### Phase 1 — CrowdStrike Falcon: WMI Persistence Hunt

**Hunt Query — Falcon Event Search (FQL):**

```sql
-- Hunt for WMI EventConsumer creation
event_simpleName=WmiActivityEvent
| search CommandLine="*CommandLineEventConsumer*"
  OR CommandLine="*ActiveScriptEventConsumer*"
| stats count by ComputerName, UserName, CommandLine
| sort -count
```

**Results — 3 hosts with anomalous WMI activity:**

```
ComputerName    UserName   CommandLine
MFG-WS-031     SYSTEM     CommandLineEventConsumer — "svchost.exe -k netsvcs"
MFG-WS-047     SYSTEM     CommandLineEventConsumer — "powershell -enc [base64]"
MFG-SRV-003    SYSTEM     ActiveScriptEventConsumer — VBScript loader
```

**Drilling into MFG-WS-031 via CrowdStrike RTR:**

```bash
# Connect via Real Time Response
> runscript -Raw "Get-WMIObject -Namespace root\subscription -Class __EventFilter"

Name:        WindowsUpdateFilter
Query:       SELECT * FROM __InstanceModificationEvent WITHIN 60
             WHERE TargetInstance ISA 'Win32_PerfFormattedData_PerfOS_System'
             AND TargetInstance.SystemUpTime >= 300
# ↑ Fires 5 minutes after every system boot — guaranteed persistence
```

```bash
> runscript -Raw "Get-WMIObject -Namespace root\subscription -Class __EventConsumer"

Name:         WindowsUpdateConsumer
CommandLine:  C:\Windows\System32\svchost.exe -k netsvcs -p
# ↑ Looks legitimate — but path check reveals it's NOT the real svchost
```

```bash
> runscript -Raw "Get-FileHash 'C:\Windows\System32\svchost.exe'"
Hash: legitimate_microsoft_hash

> runscript -Raw "Get-WMIObject __FilterToConsumerBinding -Namespace root\subscription"
# Reveals binding points to:
# C:\Windows\Temp\svchost.exe  ← DIFFERENT PATH — malicious copy
```

> **The implant named itself `svchost.exe` and was placed in `C:\Windows\Temp\` — not `System32`. WMI subscription fires 5 minutes after every boot, executing the malicious binary. Zero registry keys. Zero scheduled tasks. Traditional persistence hunting would have missed this entirely.**

