## Key Takeaways

- **Automated detection has blind spots.** WMI event subscriptions are one of the most effective persistence techniques precisely because most detection rules focus on registry keys and scheduled tasks. Hypothesis-driven hunting fills these gaps.
- **Beaconing regularity is a gift to defenders.** A 4-hour interval with ±2 second jitter is machine-generated. Humans don't operate that consistently. Zeek interval analysis surfaces this pattern reliably.
- **Coordinated log clearing is a human signal.** Automated malware rarely clears logs. When three hosts clear their Security event logs within 10 minutes of each other, a human operator is actively managing the intrusion — escalate immediately.
- **CrowdStrike Threat Graph** is one of the most powerful lateral movement reconstruction tools available — the visual attack tree across hosts dramatically accelerates scope determination in complex intrusions.
